TYPE: Test,
TARGET: power supply module output wiring,
DESCRIPTION: With the PSU still disconnected from the rest of the system, open the PSU box and trace each output cable to its internal connection. Using a multimeter in continuity mode, verify: (1) which internal node the supposed + output cable is actually connected to (battery + node after the LED/resistor junction, battery −, or somewhere else); (2) which node the supposed − output cable is connected to; and (3) whether either output cable is shorted together internally. This will reveal a miswire/crossed connection or internal short preventing 12 V from appearing across the outputs.,
RESULT: The PSU Output Cable (+) is internally tied to the battery internal resistor and the PSU green LED resistor node, and also shows a short (~1 Ω) to the battery node and to the PSU Output Cable (−). The PSU Output Cable (−) is internally tied to battery (neg), the LED cathode, and also shows a short (~1 Ω) to the same resistor node as the + cable, resulting in ~1 Ω between PSU Output Cable (+) and (−). No polarity inversion is indicated between labeled (+) and (−) cables; instead, the two PSU output cables are effectively shorted together through a low resistance path.
Current persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:
