Someone executed a (additional) diagnostic action on the system. The action (type, target_component, description, outcome) was: 
TYPE: Test,
TARGET: power supply module internal circuit (inspect schematic vs actual wiring),
DESCRIPTION: With the PSU still isolated and confirmed electrically intact, carefully compare the actual internal wiring against the intended circuit: verify that the LED/resistor branch is indeed in parallel with the battery terminals, not in series with or shorting the output nodes. Using the meter, identify the true battery (+) and (−) nodes, then map every internal connection: battery (+) to LED/resistor, LED/resistor to battery (−), and separately battery (+) and (−) to each respective output cable. Record whether any intentional low‑ohm shunt/connector or configuration (e.g., shipping jumper, test link, or mis-set selector inside the PSU) is present that ties the + and − output nodes together or routes the output through the indicator branch.,
RESULT: The battery’s negative terminal is connected to PSU Output Cable (−), and its positive node is common with PSU Output Cable (+) through the 1 Ω internal resistor; PSU Output Cables (+) and (−) thus measure about 1 Ω between them. The PSU green LED branch is wired with its resistor on PSU Output Cable (+) and its LED cathode on PSU Output Cable (−), giving ~1001 Ω between battery and LED, so the LED/resistor branch is in parallel with the output (not directly shorting it). No separate low-ohm shunt or internal jumper other than the 1 Ω battery internal resistor is tying the + and − output nodes together.
Current persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:
No circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.


