Someone executed a (additional) diagnostic action on the system. The action (type, target_component, description, outcome) was: 
TYPE: Test,
TARGET: control modules chain and load module (powered from current PSU),
DESCRIPTION: Reconnect the PSU to the full chain with all switches ON. With respect to PSU Output Cable (−) as reference, measure the voltage at: (1) PSU Output Cable (+); (2) the 12 V/0 V pair at the input of control module 1; (3) between the two cables at the output of each subsequent control module; and (4) the two cables at the load module input. At each point, also check continuity (ohms) between the local + and − lines with power removed. This will determine whether the 1 Ω internal source resistance is simply causing a large voltage drop into a downstream short or miswired module, and will locate where along the series path the effective short or misconnection occurs.,
RESULT: All switches are closed, and the PSU is supplying ~12 V, which appears correctly at Control Input Cable (+) 1 with the (−) line near 0 V; there is no POLARITY INVERSION indicated between any labeled (+) and (−) cables. Downstream of Control Output Cable (+/−) 2, the measured voltage between the (+) and (−) lines collapses to ~0.0064 V and remains at that level through all subsequent control outputs and the load input. Continuity of all measured cables is nominal, with a noted nearby anomaly that Control Input Cable (+) 3 has its 'n' port floating/disconnected from the circuit.
Current persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:
No circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.


