2026-04-21 01:33:14 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Internal wiring / connection of Control Input Cable (+) 3 port n in Control Module 3', 'Jumper between Control Input Cable (+) 3 port n and Control Output Cable (+) 3', 'Any unintended low‑ohm path from Control Input Cable (+) 3 port n to Control Output Cable (−) 3 inside Control Module 3'] hypothesis_explanation="Control module 3 is miswired internally so that the incoming + conductor is not correctly passed through the switch path to the outgoing + conductor, and instead its 'n' port of Control Input Cable (+) 3 is left floating and partially shunted toward the − line (~2.12 Ω to Control Output Cable (−) 3). As a result, downstream of module 2 the + and − lines are effectively tied together through a low resistance in module 3, causing the measured collapse of voltage to ~0 V for all subsequent modules and preventing all control LEDs and the load lamp from lighting.\n\nThe correct design is that Control Input Cable (+) 3 should route through the switch to Control Output Cable (+) 3, with the indicator LED branch from + (after the switch) to −. Instead, the observation shows that Control Input Cable (+) 3 port p is tied only to the upstream output (Output (+) 2) and itself, while port n is floating and wrongly referenced to the − side. Repairing the internal wiring so that the + input is properly connected through the switch to the + output, and eliminating the unintended 2.12 Ω path from Input (+) 3 n to Output (−) 3, should remove the downstream short, restore the 12 V rail past module 2, and allow the chain LEDs and final lamp to operate correctly."
